experience perspective,

248
00:11:20,569 --> 00:11:22,110
there are a lot of
interesting things

249
00:11:22,110 --> 00:11:24,670
to learn about
augmented reality,

250
00:11:24,670 --> 00:11:26,622
particularly how
it fits on the web.

251
00:11:26,622 --> 00:11:28,830
And it's a good reason to
start experimenting with it

252
00:11:28,830 --> 00:11:30,990
now if you're thinking
about adding it.

253
00:11:30,990 --> 00:11:34,140
So by way of example,
West Elm, who

254
00:11:34,140 --> 00:11:37,560
sells home decor and furniture,
did some in-store testing.

255
00:11:37,560 --> 00:11:40,350
And what they did was they
went to one of their stores

256
00:11:40,350 --> 00:11:42,540
and they picked four
shoppers at random.

257
00:11:42,540 --> 00:11:45,690
And they showed them a
prototype shopping website that

258
00:11:45,690 --> 00:11:47,610
incorporated augmented reality.

259
00:11:47,610 --> 00:11:48,870
Now this isn't a huge study.

260
00:11:48,870 --> 00:11:49,676
It's four shoppers.

261
00:11:49,676 --> 00:11:51,300
But they had some
interesting findings.

262
00:11:51,300 --> 00:11:53,760
And they gave us
permission to share them.

263
00:11:53,760 --> 00:11:55,260
So the first thing
that they learned

264
00:11:55,260 --> 00:11:59,140
is with these customers, the
terms AR or augmented reality,

265
00:11:59,140 --> 00:12:01,290
it's not really a
common vocabulary.

266
00:12:01,290 --> 00:12:03,960
Basic terminology,
like view in your room,

267
00:12:03,960 --> 00:12:06,390
is a better way of
telling users what to do.

268
00:12:06,390 --> 00:12:09,540
But even then, without a visual
showing what's going to happen,

269
00:12:09,540 --> 00:12:12,100
that text can really get lost
with everything else that

270
00:12:12,100 --> 00:12:13,830
is visual on the site.

271
00:12:13,830 --> 00:12:15,300
So what they're
looking at now is

272
00:12:15,300 --> 00:12:18,222
ways to add both an icon and
text so that the user has

273
00:12:18,222 --> 00:12:18,930
a call to action.

274
00:12:18,930 --> 00:12:20,400
They know what to do.

275
00:12:20,400 --> 00:12:22,224
One approach might be
to have a rotating 3D

276
00:12:22,224 --> 00:12:23,890
model so that the
user understands, hey,

277
00:12:23,890 --> 00:12:27,070
this is more than just
another image on the page.

278
00:12:27,070 --> 00:12:29,320
The next thing they learned
is that users get confused

279
00:12:29,320 --> 00:12:30,430
without clear directions.

280
00:12:30,430 --> 00:12:33,820
You can see here that there's a
delay while the user is trying

281
00:12:33,820 --> 00:12:35,600
to figure out what to do.

282
00:12:35,600 --> 00:12:36,220
Do I tap?

283
00:12:36,220 --> 00:12:38,260
Do I move my phone around?

284
00:12:38,260 --> 00:12:40,000
What is this circle
on the floor?

285
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:41,920
I've never seen this before.

286
00:12:41,920 --> 00:12:45,190
You have to actually guide users
to the path of success here.

287
00:12:45,190 --> 00:12:48,130
And West Elm is researching
clear directions as well

288
00:12:48,130 --> 00:12:50,597
as things like progress
bars and loading indicators

289
00:12:50,597 --> 00:12:52,180
so that users don't
get lost, and they

290
00:12:52,180 --> 00:12:54,388
can see how to get to the
point that they're actually

291
00:12:54,388 --> 00:12:58,970
placing furniture or an
object into the real world.

292
00:12:58,970 --> 00:13:02,230
After that, once participants
successfully placed an object,

293
00:13:02,230 --> 00:13:04,430
the most common
request was the ability

294
00:13:04,430 --> 00:13:07,880
to move it or spin it or even
remove it from the scene.

295
00:13:07,880 --> 00:13:10,594
The original placement wasn't
always where they wanted it to.

296
00:13:10,594 --> 00:13:12,260
It wasn't always clear
to users how they

297
00:13:12,260 --> 00:13:14,420
could do that, in this case.

298
00:13:14,420 --> 00:13:18,050
Another thing that they heard
from their test subjects

299
00:13:18,050 --> 00:13:20,570
as well was that
getting validation,

300
00:13:20,570 --> 00:13:23,584
that the size of the virtual
object matched the real world,

301
00:13:23,584 --> 00:13:24,500
would also be helpful.

302
00:13:24,500 --> 00:13:25,760
Because if you're
shopping for furniture,

303
00:13:25,760 --> 00:13:27,801
you want to make sure that
it fits into the space

304
00:13:27,801 --> 00:13:28,530
that you have.

305
00:13:28,530 --> 00:13:29,905
So from that
perspective, showing

306
00:13:29,905 --> 00:13:33,920
some real-world dimensions
with the model could help.

307
00:13:33,920 --> 00:13:35,500
And finally, there
was some feedback

308
00:13:35,500 --> 00:13:37,270
on how real the assets looked.

309
00:13:37,270 --> 00:13:39,430
And now this study was
particularly unique

310
00:13:39,430 --> 00:13:41,305
because West Elm was
doing it in-store.

311
00:13:41,305 --> 00:13:43,930
And so they had the opportunity
to put the virtual object right

312
00:13:43,930 --> 00:13:47,710
next to the physical object
and get real shopper feedback.

313
00:13:47,710 --> 00:13:50,200
Generally speaking,
the feedback on realism

314
00:13:50,200 --> 00:13:51,947
here was only about 6 out of 10.

315
00:13:51,947 --> 00:13:53,530
And you can see
clearly that there are

316
00:13:53,530 --> 00:13:55,250
differences between the two.

317
00:13:55,250 --> 00:13:57,610
So West Elm is looking at how
to handle typical lighting

318
00:13:57,610 --> 00:13:59,560
scenarios and also make
sure that the shadows

319
00:13:59,560 --> 00:14:02,018
underneath the object are a
little more pronounced and more

320
00:14:02,018 --> 00:14:03,166
detailed.

321
00:14:03,166 --> 00:14:04,540
So the key message
here really is

322
00:14:04,540 --> 00:14:06,320
that there's a whole lot of
things that you can learn.

323
00:14:06,320 --> 00:14:08,290
There's a lot of
streamlining going on here.

324
00:14:08,290 --> 00:14:10,420
And fundamentally,
augmented reality on the web

325
00:14:10,420 --> 00:14:13,150
has some differences from
apps where somebody might

326
00:14:13,150 --> 00:14:15,130
be installing an
augmented reality app,

327
00:14:15,130 --> 00:14:19,210
and so they're discovering it
in a completely different way.

328
00:14:19,210 --> 00:14:22,000
Despite those
challenges, I think

329
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:24,310
a telling finding
from this study

330
00:14:24,310 --> 00:14:26,080
was that three of
the four participants

331
00:14:26,080 --> 00:14:29,860
said they would absolutely,
10 out of 10, use AR,

332
00:14:29,860 --> 00:14:31,540
once they knew what
that term meant,

333
00:14:31,540 --> 00:14:34,030
to do furniture shopping.

334
00:14:34,030 --> 00:14:36,040
Now, if you're like
me and you grew up

335
00:14:36,040 --> 00:14:38,500
with commercials talking about
three out of four dentists

336
00:14:38,500 --> 00:14:40,150
recommend this
toothpaste, you probably

337
00:14:40,150 --> 00:14:42,760
all wondered, what does
that fourth dentist think?

338
00:14:42,760 --> 00:14:44,590
Does it rot teeth?

339
00:14:44,590 --> 00:14:48,180
And the answer here
is actually maybe.

340
00:14:48,180 --> 00:14:49,560
So three people absolutely.

341
00:14:49,560 --> 00:14:50,610
One person maybe.

342
00:14:50,610 --> 00:14:52,697
I personally visualize
that as these

343
00:14:52,697 --> 00:14:54,780
are people shopping for
home decor, and they said,

344
00:14:54,780 --> 00:14:55,410
would you use this?

345
00:14:55,410 --> 00:14:56,430
And they're like maybe.

346
00:14:56,430 --> 00:14:57,720
I'm here to buy a couch.

347
00:14:57,720 --> 00:15:00,550
But I don't actually
think that's how it went.

348
00:15:00,550 --> 00:15:03,330
But the point here is that
three people said absolutely.

349
00:15:03,330 --> 00:15:05,700
Pulled from random, three
people said absolutely.

350
00:15:05,700 --> 00:15:06,631
It's a strong signal.

351
00:15:06,631 --> 00:15:08,130
It's also consistent
with what we've

352
00:15:08,130 --> 00:15:10,260
heard from partners
and users who

353
00:15:10,260 --> 00:15:13,440
see value and be able to
visualize 3D objects ideally

354
00:15:13,440 --> 00:15:16,390
in the real world.

355
00:15:16,390 --> 00:15:18,600
So if you're thinking
about experimenting this

356
00:15:18,600 --> 00:15:20,400
and you're thinking about
adding this to your website,

357
00:15:20,400 --> 00:15:22,830
let's talk a little bit about
how you can build things.

358
00:15:22,830 --> 00:15:25,110
Chris mentioned the flags you
can enable a little bit earlier

359
00:15:25,110 --> 00:15:27,526
in the presentation, but let's
talk about how you actually

360
00:15:27,526 --> 00:15:29,060
add the immersive experience.

361
00:15:29,060 --> 00:15:31,417
So you could write
WebGL code directly.

362
00:15:31,417 --> 00:15:33,000
And if you're doing
augmented reality,

363
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:36,030
that would be over top
of the camera feed.

364
00:15:36,030 --> 00:15:37,410
That's one way you can do it.

365
00:15:37,410 --> 00:15:40,200
Generally, we recommend
using a library to help.

366
00:15:40,200 --> 00:15:42,510
For example, three.js
is a helper library

367
00:15:42,510 --> 00:15:44,280
for 3D graphics
on the web, and it

368
00:15:44,280 --> 00:15:47,280
takes care of a lot of the
heavy lifting for 3D geometry

369
00:15:47,280 --> 00:15:48,420
management and rendering.

370
00:15:48,420 --> 00:15:49,795
And it makes it
so you don't have

371
00:15:49,795 --> 00:15:51,730
to work with WebGL directly.

372
00:15:51,730 --> 00:15:54,327
So let's look at an example
of how three and WebXR can

373
00:15:54,327 --> 00:15:54,910
work together.

374
00:15:54,910 --> 00:15:57,160
We're not going to cover the
whole process of creating

375
00:15:57,160 --> 00:15:58,720
a WebXR session
and doing all that,

376
00:15:58,720 --> 00:16:01,110
but we are going to look at
how a virtual object can be

377
00:16:01,110 --> 00:16:03,400
placed into a real-world scene.

378
00:16:03,400 --> 00:16:05,490
And we're going to do that
with a narrow use case,

379
00:16:05,490 --> 00:16:08,785
in this case, putting a reticle
onto a real world surface.

380
00:16:08,785 --> 00:16:10,660
For those who haven't
heard that term before,

381
00:16:10,660 --> 00:16:12,090
a reticle is an indicator.

382
00:16:12,090 --> 00:16:14,130
In this case, you can see
it as it moves around.

383
00:16:14,130 --> 00:16:15,780
And it's typically
a user interface

384
00:16:15,780 --> 00:16:18,270
construct so that the user
knows what they can do.

385
00:16:18,270 --> 00:16:21,820
You saw some of this in the
West Elm screenshots earlier.

386
00:16:21,820 --> 00:16:24,270
So what we're going to
do first in this case

387
00:16:24,270 --> 00:16:26,850
is take the mesh for the
reticle, which, in our case,

388
00:16:26,850 --> 00:16:30,090
is a flat circle, and we'll
add it to the three scene.

389
00:16:30,090 --> 00:16:31,770
It's worth noting
we'd like the reticle

390
00:16:31,770 --> 00:16:33,630
to be about half a meter wide.

391
00:16:33,630 --> 00:16:36,210
And so it's worth noting
that the WebXR device

392
00:16:36,210 --> 00:16:39,240
API locks the coordinate
system of the real world

393
00:16:39,240 --> 00:16:40,740
to the virtual world.

394
00:16:40,740 --> 00:16:42,300
And what that
means is that, one,

395
00:16:42,300 --> 00:16:45,240
in WebGL or the virtual
space or in three,

396
00:16:45,240 --> 00:16:47,370
one unit is one meter
in the real world.

397
00:16:47,370 --> 00:16:49,060
10 units is 10 meters.

398
00:16:49,060 --> 00:16:51,870
So in this case, if our
mesh is half a unit wide,

399
00:16:51,870 --> 00:16:55,920
it means it'll appear as half
a meter in the real world.

400
00:16:55,920 --> 00:16:57,420
Next, what we're
going to want to do

401
00:16:57,420 --> 00:17:00,030
is actually render the
reticle over the camera

402
00:17:00,030 --> 00:17:01,770
on real-world geometry.

403
00:17:01,770 --> 00:17:03,990
But to do that, we need to
know where the real world

404
00:17:03,990 --> 00:17:05,579
geometry is.

405
00:17:05,579 --> 00:17:08,339
The WebXR device API
includes the capability

406
00:17:08,339 --> 00:17:10,210
to do a hit test,
which is firing

407
00:17:10,210 --> 00:17:13,079
a ray into the real world
and getting intersection

408
00:17:13,079 --> 00:17:15,520
points with real-world
surfaces, so, for example,

409
00:17:15,520 --> 00:17:17,994
taking a ray from my
eye, down into the stage,

410
00:17:17,994 --> 00:17:20,160
and then getting the
intersection point of where I'm

411
00:17:20,160 --> 00:17:22,740
looking on the stage, but
also the normal facing up,

412
00:17:22,740 --> 00:17:26,030
so I know where the surface is
and what direction it's facing.

413
00:17:26,030 --> 00:17:28,202
Now, in order to do
that, you need a ray.

414
00:17:28,202 --> 00:17:30,660
And a good example of some of
the things three can help you

415
00:17:30,660 --> 00:17:33,780
with is a ray caster function,
which I don't show here.

416
00:17:33,780 --> 00:17:36,360
But it will let you get the
origin and the direction

417
00:17:36,360 --> 00:17:37,860
of the ray that
you're going to fire

418
00:17:37,860 --> 00:17:39,339
into the scene from the camera.

419
00:17:39,339 --> 00:17:40,630
So we've already got that here.

420
00:17:40,630 --> 00:17:43,140
And what we're going to do is
pass that into the hit test

421
00:17:43,140 --> 00:17:45,891
API with WebXR.

422
00:17:45,891 --> 00:17:48,140
And then what we'll do is
we'll take the return value.

423
00:17:48,140 --> 00:17:50,300
We'll actually possibly
get a list of things,

424
00:17:50,300 --> 00:17:52,280
because it might be
more than one object

425
00:17:52,280 --> 00:17:54,560
behind the first hit.

426
00:17:54,560 --> 00:17:56,690
We'll take the first
one, the closest,

427
00:17:56,690 --> 00:17:59,210
and we'll convert
the position that we

428
00:17:59,210 --> 00:18:01,580
got into a three.js
matrix, and then

429
00:18:01,580 --> 00:18:03,769
we'll use that to set the
position of the reticle.

430
00:18:03,769 --> 00:18:05,060
And at that point, you're done.

431
00:18:05,060 --> 00:18:07,850
The reticle is now positioned
so that it will render directly

432
00:18:07,850 --> 00:18:12,129
over the real-world object that
was detected from that ray.

433
00:18:12,129 --> 00:18:13,670
Now, it's worth
reiterating that this

434
00:18:13,670 --> 00:18:16,130
works because the virtual
coordinate system matches

435
00:18:16,130 --> 00:18:17,117
the real world one.

436
00:18:17,117 --> 00:18:19,200
And obviously, I skipped
over a lot of steps here,

437
00:18:19,200 --> 00:18:21,491
but the point really is that
you can combine frameworks

438
00:18:21,491 --> 00:18:23,300
like three js with WebXR.

439
00:18:23,300 --> 00:18:26,360
And it's fairly straightforward
if you know 3D programming

440
00:18:26,360 --> 00:18:28,540
basics.

441
00:18:28,540 --> 00:18:32,770
But some of you might not
know 3D programming basics.

442
00:18:32,770 --> 00:18:34,270
And the fact is
that if you've tried

443
00:18:34,270 --> 00:18:37,090
to add a 3D model to
your site, you probably

444
00:18:37,090 --> 00:18:38,740
know already it's
not super easy.

445
00:18:38,740 --> 00:18:42,970
3D models can be pretty complex
both to read and to display.

446
00:18:42,970 --> 00:18:45,610
We saw that, even in
the West Elm example,

447
00:18:45,610 --> 00:18:47,435
there were user
experience considerations.

448
00:18:47,435 --> 00:18:49,810
If you're starting from scratch,
you have to think about,

449
00:18:49,810 --> 00:18:52,226
how do I want to rotate objects,
allow people to move them

450
00:18:52,226 --> 00:18:53,870
around, and so forth?

451
00:18:53,870 --> 00:18:55,810
And then there's also
responsive design.

452
00:18:55,810 --> 00:18:58,944
If you want this to work
on mobile and desktop,

453
00:18:58,944 --> 00:19:00,610
even if you're just
doing a simple model

454
00:19:00,610 --> 00:19:04,180
and a turntable view, you have
to know how to handle resizing.

455
00:19:04,180 --> 00:19:06,500
Do you need to display
a poster image on mobile

456
00:19:06,500 --> 00:19:09,070
to prevent the download
of the 3D geometry

457
00:19:09,070 --> 00:19:11,260
until the user
actually wants it?

458
00:19:11,260 --> 00:19:14,080
For newer technology,
like augmented reality,

459
00:19:14,080 --> 00:19:16,750
ideally, you'd be able to take
advantage and progressively

460
00:19:16,750 --> 00:19:18,970
enhance and use some
of the capabilities

461
00:19:18,970 --> 00:19:20,800
on different platforms
even if they're not

462
00:19:20,800 --> 00:19:22,820
available in all browsers.

463
00:19:22,820 --> 00:19:25,892
And as WebXR comes out and
starts moving to stable,

464
00:19:25,892 --> 00:19:27,100
it's one more thing to learn.

465
00:19:27,100 --> 00:19:28,224
It's one more thing to add.

466
00:19:28,224 --> 00:19:30,910
So just know that if you've
experimented with this before

467
00:19:30,910 --> 00:19:34,464
and you found it a little
bit tricky, you're not alone.

468
00:19:34,464 --> 00:19:36,880
So to that end, the team has
been looking at this problem.

469
00:19:36,880 --> 00:19:40,600
And we recently made public
an early version of a 3D

470
00:19:40,600 --> 00:19:42,220
model viewer web component.

471
00:19:42,220 --> 00:19:43,857
This is really,
really early, but it

472
00:19:43,857 --> 00:19:46,190
does some things today to
make life a little bit easier.

473
00:19:46,190 --> 00:19:49,460
And the reason we released it
early was to get your feedback.

474
00:19:49,460 --> 00:19:51,460
To give you some context
for this web component,

475
00:19:51,460 --> 00:19:53,220
there's three things
we're trying to do.

476
00:19:53,220 --> 00:19:54,970
The first is we want
you to be able to add

477
00:19:54,970 --> 00:19:58,090
3D models to your site without
having to learn 3D programming

478
00:19:58,090 --> 00:19:59,960
or writing 3D code.

479
00:19:59,960 --> 00:20:02,650
The second is we want it to
work well and responsibly

480
00:20:02,650 --> 00:20:04,930
across browsers and across
different device form

481
00:20:04,930 --> 00:20:07,030
factors with
progressive enhancement

482
00:20:07,030 --> 00:20:09,910
to take advantage
of capabilities

483
00:20:09,910 --> 00:20:12,020
on browsers where
they're available.

484
00:20:12,020 --> 00:20:13,990
And then the third
goal is that as new API

485
00:20:13,990 --> 00:20:15,959
ships, such as the
WebXR device API,

486
00:20:15,959 --> 00:20:18,250
we want the component to
start taking advantage of them

487
00:20:18,250 --> 00:20:19,624
so that you don't
have to keep up

488
00:20:19,624 --> 00:20:23,710
to date with all of the
changes that are coming out.

489
00:20:23,710 --> 00:20:25,502
So, like I said,
it is super early,

490
00:20:25,502 --> 00:20:26,710
but we've made some progress.

491
00:20:26,710 --> 00:20:28,418
And so I want to give
you a sense of what

492
00:20:28,418 --> 00:20:29,580
the component can do today.

493
00:20:29,580 --> 00:20:30,954
Let's run through
a few examples.

494
00:20:30,954 --> 00:20:33,460
And this is the first one,
the simplest use case,

495
00:20:33,460 --> 00:20:35,910
